<h1>To Robert Dinwiddie</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">To the Honourable Robert Dinwiddie, Esquire, Governour.<br/>Honble Sir,</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">[Winchester, 25 June 1756]</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>I doubt not but your Honour will be as much surprized, as I have been concerned and vexed at my stay here.</p>
<p>When I left Williamsburgh, I did it with a design to proceed with the utmost expedition to Fort Cumberland. In order thereto, I arrived at Fredericksburgh to Dinner, the day after I left your Honour, at one oclock; and gave the officer, posted at
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-03-02-pb-0223">[223]</span>
that place, a list of such tools as were wanted to build the chain of Forts; and ordered they might be sent by a waggon, pressed for that purpose, immediately to Winchester:<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> To which place I repai[re]d to get every thing in readiness, and wait their coming to escort them to Fort Cumberland. After I had been here two or three days, I received a Letter enclosing a list of the Tools from the Officer; who informed me, that he had, according to order, dispatched them in a waggon, hired for that purpose;<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> for which <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">waggon</span> I have been waiting with the greatest impatience and uneasiness imaginable. How to account for this delay, I am quite at a loss (as I am certain they were sent;) unless the Waggoner has lost his Horses or run off with the waggon and contents. I thought it needless to proceed without them as nothing can be done for want of Tools. I have sent two or three Expresses to hurry them on; and shall make no delay when they arrive.</p>
<p>I intend to take the advice of a council of war (when I arrive at Fort Cumberland) about the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Line</span> on which these Forts are to be erected &amp;c. and shall visit all the Ground that I conveniently can, and direct the Building.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0003-ptr">3</a></p>
<p>It is a work that must be conducted extremely tedious; for these reasonsviztThe scarcity of tools; smallness of our numbers; and want of Conductors. The strength of our Forces will not admit of many divisions; because in that case each party may probably be demolished. We can therefore, only attempt, with such men as can be drawn out of the Garrisons already established, to build fort after fort: and not by attempting too many at a time; and thereby run the risque of having the whole demolished. To go on in the manner above-mentioned must be extremely tedious; unless your Honour will be pleased to put the Militia that are upon our southern frontiers under the command of Captain Hoggand order them to begin on the Mayo River and proceed in their Buildings until they meet our parties which will advance to the southwardI can point out no other method at present to expedite this necessary work. If your Honour approves of this scheme and will let me know by ExpressI shall dispatch another to Captain Hogg to inform him thereof; and shall enclose him such a plan as the whole will be erected by. Your Honours orders to militia, and indeed to
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-03-02-pb-0224">[224]</span>
the Inhabitants of those partsto assist with their advice in fixing upon the places; and with their labour, in forwarding the workmust be absolutely necessary.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0004" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0004-ptr">4</a></p>
<p>Your Honour never gave me a decisive answer to a question I asked, about giving the Field Officers CompaniesFor which reason I have presumed to repeat it again, because there are two companies now vacant, by the death of Captain John Mercer, and the resignation of Captain Savage:<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0005" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0005-ptr">5</a> and should either be given to the Field Officers, or oldest Lieutenants. There is no advantage can possibly arise to the Field Officers by having Companies (but trouble there certainly will) as they are allowed, I suppose, the same pay <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">now</span> as though they <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">had</span>.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0006" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0006-ptr">6</a></p>
<p>The only reason that urges me to repeat it is, because I look upon this to be a singular instance to the contraryand running the Country to the additional expence of three supernumary Captains. Two hundred and forty-six Draughts are the total number brought in<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0007" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0007-ptr">7</a>out of which number several have deserted; three were dischargedbeing quite unfit for Service (and indeed several more <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">ought</span> to be, if men were not so scarce:) and there remain now in confinement six Quakers; who will neither bear arms, work, receive provisions or pay, or do any thing that tends, in any respect, to self-defence. I should be glad of your Honours directions how to proceed with them.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0008" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0008-ptr">8</a></p>
<p>I can not yet return your Honour the names of the Volunteers that will be appointed to the vacancies; but as soon as I arrive at Fort Cumberland shall acquaint you, according to request.</p>
<p>Governour Sharpe is building a Fort on Potomack River, about fifteen miles above Conogochieg, which may be of great service towards the protection of our people on that side. It is thought the Fort will cost the Province of Maryland near thirty thousand pounds, before it is finished.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0009" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0009-ptr">9</a> I am &amp;c.</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">G:W.</p>
</div>
<div class="postscript">
<p>P.S. I should take it very kind if your Honour would send a few more blank commissions: There are six or seven vacancies, and the promotions will require more.</p>
<p style="text-indent: 0;">Winchester: June 25th 1756.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0217-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Book Copy: letters copied into a bound letter-book ]">LB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>GW left Williamsburg on 10 June. He gave these orders to Capt. Joshua Lewis at Fredericksburg, perhaps verbally.</p>

</div>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-03-02-pb-0225">[225]</span>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>The letter has not been found, but it was probably from Joshua Lewis, who was in charge at Fredericksburg (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0221" class="document">George Mercer to Lewis, 26 June 1756</a><span class="choice deletion" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Deleted: ', printed below' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2014-11-06]]&lt;/span&gt; ]"><img alt="deletion" src="images/deletion_mark-trans.png" style="border:none;vertical-align: text-bottom; padding-right:2px"/></span>).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>For references to choosing the sites of the forts to be built, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0200&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-03-02-0200-fn-0003#GEWN-02-03-02-0200-fn-0003" class="document">Dinwiddie to GW, 12 June 1756, n.3</a>. See also <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0200&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-03-02-0200-fn-0004#GEWN-02-03-02-0200-fn-0004" class="document">note 4</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>On 1 July Dinwiddie authorized GW to give Peter Hog directions for building forts on the frontier in Augusta County. At a council of war GW held at Fort Cumberland on 10 July to decide how and where the chain of forts should be built, it was agreed that Hog should begin building the forts to the south of Fort Dinwiddie. GW issued Hog instructions to this effect on 21 July 1756.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>John Savage of Prince William County served with GW at Fort Necessity in 1754, and he had been captain of a company in the Viriginia Regiment since September 1755.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>GW brought up the matter of assigning companies to field officers in the Virginia Regiment in <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0001-0001" class="document">his letter to Dinwiddie of 16 April</a> and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0169" class="document">again on 23 May</a>. Dinwiddie wrote on 1 July that he very much approved of the field officers having companies. GW and Lt. Col. Adam Stephen both assumed command of companies in the regiment in July 1756.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0007-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0007">7</a>

   <p>For discussions of the drafting of the militia and the collecting of the recruits, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0099-0001&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-03-02-0099-0001-fn-0004#GEWN-02-03-02-0099-0001-fn-0004" class="document">Dinwiddie to GW, 8 May 1756, n.4</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0189&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-03-02-0189-fn-0002#GEWN-02-03-02-0189-fn-0002" class="document">GWs Orders, 2 June 1756, n.2</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0008-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0008">8</a>

   <p>The six Quakers appear to have remained on the frontier until all of the militia was discharged on 1 Dec. 1756. Among the militiamen discharged at that time were three Quakers from Hanover County (John Harris, Cornel Harris, and Archelaus Stanley) and three from neighboring New Kent County (John Ellison, William Ellison, and Zechariah Stanley). For Dinwiddies directions, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0227" class="document">Dinwiddie to GW, 1 July 1756</a>. See also <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0289" class="document">GW to Dinwiddie, 4 Aug.</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0319" class="document">Dinwiddie to GW, 19 Aug. 1756</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0009-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0217-fn-0009">9</a>

   <p>For Horatio Sharpes radically different estimate of the cost of Fort Frederick, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0208-0001&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-03-02-0208-0001-fn-0006#GEWN-02-03-02-0208-0001-fn-0006" class="document">Robert Stewart to GW, 20 June 1756, n.6</a>.</p>

</div>
</div>
